📽 by @latestkruger 

Leopard works her ass off to fill her belly, but unfortunately it was not to be. 

The screams of the warthog surely tipped off the nearby lioness, who luckily (for her anyway) decided to investigate. She ended up scoring a generous offering from the leopard, who just spent the last 20 minutes or so subduing the warthog, only to have to ditch it to save her own skin. 

As formidable a hunter as she is, the leopard would risk serious - maybe even mortal injury in order to defend her kill from the larger lioness, and she had to make her decision quickly as the lioness closed in on her position. 

This perfectly illustrates the reasoning behind the leopards preference for arboreal dining, because staying on the ground just serves to keep the door open for kleptoparasites looking for an easy lunch.

node.text:
📽 by @latestkruger

A serene afternoon of grazing is turned on its ear, as the leopardess makes her move. 

The real impressive part (IMO) is how quickly the leopard reacts to the impalas attempt to leap over her while she's closing the gap. If she didn't execute the jump at that exact moment, the impala likely would have escaped and the leopard would have to go back to the drawing board to satisfy her hunger. 

Since they are solitary hunters, stalking as a hunting method saves the leopard's energy for when it counts, as slowly maneuvering into striking range is much less costly than a flat out sprint and chase. For example, if she needs to bail, she'll have the energy to do so, whereas sprinting will leave her with less fuel in the tank to make her escape. 

An exit strategy always needs to be considered when you've only got yourself to lean on. 

#natureismetal
#keepnaturemetal

📽 by @latestkruger 

An erratic elephant bullies a hoard of hippopotami after losing a contact lense in the local watering hole. 

It's no secret that hippopotamus are not to be messed with. They are categorized as one of the most aggressive and dangerous animals on earth, even towards other extremely menacing animals like crocodiles who live along side them. 

Luckily, super aggressive doesn't mean super dumb. Even a large group of them knows better than to mess with a pissed of pachyderm, who could presumably stuff multiple hippos into the african savannahs equivalent of a gym locker with ease. 

Near the end of the clip, the same elephant targets a baby hippo with impunity. This part alone tells you all you need to know about hippo/elephant relations, because if another animal did anything like that within range of a mother hippopotamus the response would be swift and utterly barbaric.

📽 by @carlostorresart

A common brown lemur eating baby magpies.

Add them to the already extensive list of animals that normally stick to a herbivorous diet, but will on occasion branch out and consume the flesh of another animal when the opportunity presents itself.

A few other animals that have been observed behaving in this manner include:

Deer
Cows
Hippos
Goats
Sheep
Horses

The prevailing theory behind this behavior is a nutritional deficiency in either salt, iron, protein or calcium.

Deer especially are known to go off menu when they are growing their antlers for the upcoming rut, researchers cite an increased demand for nutrients to explain the deer seeking their dietary boost.

Deer target nestling songbirds as their nests are usually on the ground and the small birds dont put up much of a fight.

Very similar to the strategy the lemur employs in this video

📽 by @latestkruger 

Hyenas pick away at an injured rhino. 

Seeing as this rhinos driver side (left) leg has seen better days, it's no wonder that the hyenas are laser focused on just him and practically ignoring the rest of the bunch. 

The cold logic employed by the aggressors here is simple: this rhino is not able bodied enough to run away, or mount as formidable a defense as the other bulls in the group. In its weakened state, the hyenas can focus on causing a death by a thousand cuts without worrying as much about repercussions. 

This would be a different story altogether if the other rhinos were to help him out in any capacity, but they seem to have him on the 'better you than me' list.

It is safe to assume that the hyenas eventually lost interest or were enticed by an easier meal and moved on, because this rhino was ultimately euthanized by veterinarians at KNP, as nothing could be done about his broken leg.

📽 via @latestkruger 

Black-backed jackal takes a marabou stork down for the 1,2,3. 

Jackals, along with foxes, coyotes, skunks, martens, raccoons and otters, meet the technical requirements to be classified as mesocarnivores. 

Mesocarnivore (meso=middle) play an essential role in the function of an ecosystem, especially in areas where apex predators have been eliminated. 

Their smaller size, along with a marked divergence in their behavior and ecology allow them to adapt and thrive in a range of habitats where larger carnivores/omnivores wouldn't. 

For those looking for an example of how easily a mesocarnivore can adjust, just look at how smoothly coyotes adapted to surviving on the outskirts of some suburban/urban human strongholds. 

For better or for worse, they integrated themselves effortlessly and are thriving where larger predators simply wouldn't be able to without setting off alarm bells. 

There are advantages to being middle management...

📽 by @latestkruger

Lions go to work on a cape buffalo. 

Lions, as formidable and capable as they are, must work as a team if they are to have any shot at taking down a cape buffalo. 

Unlike some other members of its family (domestic cattle, water buffalo) the cape buffalo's might has never been harnessed to serve humans. They remain wild, free and dangerous as ever. 

It is believed that cape buffalo have killed more big game hunters than any other african animal. Mature bulls can weigh anywhere between 500 - 1000kg (1102 - 2204lbs) and they can move it - top speed for a cape buffalo hovers around 56km/h (35mph)
Combine speed with the sheer mass of the animal, the solid homegrown helmet/horns that grow 1m+ (3.28ft) across, add to this their general predisposition for grouchy behavior and the "Black Death" moniker for cape buffalo starts to make a hell of a lot of sense. 

Yes, the lions won this round, but they had to "concentrate all fire on that super star destroyer" to get over the goal line.

#natureismetal

📽 by @latestkruger 

Hyena finds a live cape buffalo stuck in the mud. 

Unable to move and eaten alive. As far as ways to die stack up, this has to be one of the absolute worst imaginable. 

From the perspective of the spotted hyena, it's the greatest day ever. She doesn't need to waste time or energy killing the animal, because there is little chance of injury, she just digs in and goes for it. 

Nature is unforgiving in all respects, which was the core motivation for the inception of this account. 

There are no do overs, there are no trial runs, a mistake as simple as walking in mud that is deeper than you anticipated can cost you your life, your death can be quick or it can last hours, it can sometimes last days or more when an infection takes hold. 

The suffering endured is immense and thoroughly immeasurable. For every instance we may witness where the misery is unbearable there are 1000s more that occur unseen, and some of these are just as bad or much much worse. 

The entire point of this post and ultimately this account, is to reflect on the brutality that we are fortunate enough to be removed from almost entirely, and to respect the lives of the animals that don't have a choice in the matter. 

You might see this and say it's gratuitous and unnecessary, just know that I disagree with that sentiment whole-heartedly. 

#natureismetal
#keepnaturemetal

📽 by @latestkruger 

Mother wildebeest and leopard fight over injured wildebeest calf. 

The mother's behavior might be misinterpreted as aggression towards the calf, but I believe she is trying to get the young one on its feet again so they can flee the scene. 

This was obviously in vain, but at least she tried. Some animal mothers will straight up ditch their kids and have new ones rather than risk injury/death defending the existing ones.

This might seem cold-blooded as hell, but it is ultimately the correct course of action in most cases - including this one.

Play the Heavy
•
📸 by @jens_cullmann

Male lion and his baby elephant kill.

The average gestation period (pregnancy durarion) of an african elephant is 645 days, which is roughly 21 months.

All that time it takes to create a life, just to have it extinguished in an instant. It feels bad, it doesn't seem fair.

But there is no fair.

Whatever comes down the pipe,  it is dealt with. 

The loss of a child, while absolutely devastating and soul-crushing, is not the end.

Yes, at the very least it will take close to 2 years for the mom to have another child, and in that time so many different things can and will happen.

The whole thing is a huge gamble, this could happen a second time, imagine how much that would hurt - to relive this all over again?

Why bother!?

Because the urge to reproduce is embedded in the genetic code of every living thing on planet earth.

The purpose of life is to create life, natural selection has made it so over millions of years by selecting the organisms that are most successful at reproducing, which gives the next generation the best chance of passing on their genes, and so on.

One death, ten deaths, ten thousand deaths, they don't even register in the grand order of things, as long as the zeal to reproduce remains unfettered and these beings are allowed to proliferate indefinitely.

Life on Earth depends on it.

node.text:
Indiscriminate Brutality
•
📸 by @kurtjaybertels 

Nile crocodile with a mouthful of zebra foal 

Your average nile crocodile consumes roughly 50 meals per year. While most of these beasts live in remote areas away from people, their large population dictates that human encounters are inevitable. 

And while solid statistics are hard to come by, it is estimated that approximately 200 people die each year in the jaws of a nile crocodile. 

If you were to look at the world through their eyes, this might make a little more sense. In extreme circumstances, adult crocodiles are able to live off of their own stored up energy for over a year, meaning they can survive without a meal for at least that long. 

The crocs that go long stretches without eating aren't on a new fad diet, trying to look their best for next year's mass migration, they are starving.

Opportunistic in nature, they will take anything they can get, including a hapless villager that might be too close to the wrong rivers edge. 

Other elements contribute to these crocodile/human interactions, but one of the main ones seems to be the outside temperature.

Crocodiles are cold-blooded, meaning they draw their energy and warmth from the sun - so the hotter it is, they more active they are. Inversely, when its cold they are lethergic and passive. 

So not only are they stalwart survivalists, they are also solar powered.

No Sweat
•
📽 by @zookeeper_dan

Scrub python climbing a tree with ease.

The amethystine python, named for the milky iridescent sheen on its scales, is the 6 largest snake in the world and the largest snake on the Australian continent.

They are non-venomous, they kill their prey by constriction - a method employed by all snakes in the python family.

Constriction essentially cuts off bloodflow (and therefore, oxygen) to the vital organs, leading to unconsciousness, followed by cardiac arrest, and eventually death.

Australian pythons prey on birds, bats, rats, possums and other small mammals, and larger specimens have been observed consuming wallabies.

Stage 5 Clinger
•
📸 by @girishgowda.c

Epomis beetle larvae feeding on a shrub  (Pseudophilautus) froglet.

These ground beetle larvae feed exclusively on amphibians (frogs especially), they use prey-like movements and lure frogs to them by looking like an easy meal.

Once they are close enough, the beetle grabs and locks on to them using their sharp double jaw, which pierces deep into the frogs body.

Once its latched, it will liquefy and suck on the bodily fluids of its prey, reducing the frog to a pile of froggy bones.

Sometimes, the frog succeeds in eating the epomis beetle larvae, but the victory is short lived as it will usually vomit the predator up and get attacked by it anyway.

It is one of the few instances of a former prey item evolving to prey on its former predator.

node.text:
All In A Day's Work
•
📽 by @nickkleer 

Even with home field advantage, the caiman can do little to stop a dominant and relentless assault by the jaguar. 

It is truly impossible to take two animals that live in two different ecosystems, let alone on two vastly different continents, and compare them to one another, but I honestly feel that the "king of the jungle" moniker belongs to the jaguar. 

Lions are, without a doubt, the tippy top of their respective food chain. Their very presence on open savannah demands respect, because with the exception of a few of the larger fauna, the possibility that a herdmate or two have seen their last sunrise, whether they know it or not, is an absolute possibility. 

But consider that with one literal ocean between them, the solitary jaguar uses stealth and deception to fucking torpedo out of trees into a foreign, watery domain to pluck the natives out against their will. Caiman might not be as large as crocodiles or alligators, but they are no slouches when it comes to hunting either, and they do get pretty large. 

For instance, black caima(the largest of the species) can grow up to 13ft (4m) long and weigh close to 1100lbs (500kg) but jaguars hunt them just the same, along with everything else within their range that possesses a heartbeat. Even turtles! Their bite force allows them to plow right through the shells and dine on delights forbidden to those who possess inferior bite might. 

Like I said at the beginning, the comparison is impossible, but as you can see, I've already made up my mind about the name. It does helps that jaguar actually live in, and dominate the jungle. 

What say you?

One Bite, Everybody Knows The Rules
•
📸 by @rickmears

Mako shark sporting some massive hull damage, cause by another much larger shark. 

My guess is this was the result of the mako veering too close to an ever-hungry great white shark, although a tiger shark could have caused a similar degree of carnage. my money is on the white shark. 

This location, which is somewhere off the coast of New Smyrna Beach in Florida, sees both of these species of shark cycle in and out, so either one could be the culprit here. 

Alright, mako review time.

Today were at the New Smyrna Beach Inlet. I love this area, waters warm, nice scenery, can't stay here all the time because you know, us sharks gotta keep it moving. That being said I gotta say this - I'm in the water, everybody get out of the water, it's me, I'm not a white shark, I'm a GREAT white shark, you should have known better than to get near any and all of this in the first place, but low and behold, you did not... now we are where we are. 

Anyway here we go, one bite everybody knows the rules (long pause) mmmmm not bad.... I think.... I think this guy may have swallowed a few too many license plates, but.... I mean, I've had worse than this... have you ever tried a rotting whale carcass? This is so much better in comparison but still somehow not great either.... I'm gonna go.... 5.5? He was pretty fast and put up a great fight before I owned his ass, but the experience left a bad taste in my mouth... and that's it, New Smyrna Beach Inlet mako review, 5.5... short and sweet - tell your friends, rate review subscribe to my SharkTube, peace out

📽 by @latestkruger 

Leopard works her ass off to fill her belly, but unfortunately it was not to be. 

The screams of the warthog surely tipped off the nearby lioness, who luckily (for her anyway) decided to investigate. She ended up scoring a generous offering from the leopard, who just spent the last 20 minutes or so subduing the warthog, only to have to ditch it to save her own skin. 

As formidable a hunter as she is, the leopard would risk serious - maybe even mortal injury in order to defend her kill from the larger lioness, and she had to make her decision quickly as the lioness closed in on her position. 

This perfectly illustrates the reasoning behind the leopards preference for arboreal dining, because staying on the ground just serves to keep the door open for kleptoparasites looking for an easy lunch.

Two For The Price Of One
•
📸 by @jens_cullmann

Lioness and a gemsbok calf she pulled from the womb of its recently deceased mother.

Lions are the only cats (with the exception of male cheetah coalitions) that live in groups. The size of each pride may vary, but they max out at around 40 cats and consist of mostly female lions.

All of the prides lionesses are related, and female cubs commonly remain with the pride as they age.

Young males will eventually branch out and establish their own prides by killing or casting out the dominant male of another group of lions.

Once the takeover is complete, the new leader of the pride will systematically murder the old males offspring, so he can pass on and nurture his own bloodline instead of the ousted ones.

Save A Hare, Ride A Mule Deer
•
📽 by @tb.357 

Lynx jumps a muley in the snow 

Believe it or not, the lynx emerged victorious in this bout. I present the photo, expertly spliced onto the very end of this footage by yours truly, as exhibit A. 

Lynx do not normally hunt prey this large. Snowshoe hares are their nourriture préférée, so much so that the two populations are quite literally attached at the hip - if the hare population dips year over year, there will be a decrease in the lynx population as well. If it increases, the lynx will collectively ramp up their reproduction efforts to meet this feast head-on. 

When these dips in their mobile snack population occur, the lynx expand their menu to include birds, squirrels, voles, along with young dall's sheep, juvenile caribou and sub-adult mule deer.

Hung Out To Die
•
📸 by @bjergej
Via @stevenrinella 

The remains of a long dead caribou, straightened out by gravity after having paid his debt to the earth. 

It is one thing to have bad luck, which is what I would call the act of tripping/slipping into that gap in the first place, but it is quite another to have the unholy misfortune of being forced to endure your eventual demise, minute by minute, hour by hour, instead of just falling to your death. 

I seriously hope my hypothetical scenario is incorrect, and that the caribou broke its neck on impact, because I would not wish such a terrible fate on my most hated nemesis.
